=09
	<h6>SPSS Statistics</h6>
	<h2><strong>Example</strong> used in this guide</h2>

	<p>A school teacher wanted to examine whether pass rates increased as stud=
ents had more time to study. In this hypothetical study, 60 students were r=
ecruited to take part. All students were first given a "surprise exam" to t=
est their current knowledge. They were then given a "mock exam" two weeks l=
ater before they took a "final exam" a further two weeks later. Students' p=
erformance in the exams were assessed in terms of a "pass" or "fail".</p>=
=20

	<p>Due to the same students being measured on three occasions (i.e., durin=
g the "surprise", "mock" and "final" exam), we have repeated measures. We a=
lso have a dependent variable that is dichotomous with two mutually exclusi=
ve categories (i.e., "Failed" and "Passed"). As a result, Cochran's <em>Q</=
em> test is the appropriate choice to analyse the data.</p>
=09
	<h6>SPSS Statistics</h6>
	<h2><strong>Data setup</strong> in SPSS Statistics to carry out Cochran's =
<em>Q</em> test</h2>

	<p>For Cochran's <em>Q</em> test, you will have at least three variables (=
i.e., as many variables as you have related groups). In our example, we hav=
e three related groups =E2=80=93 the "surprise exam", "mock exam" and "fina=
l exam" =E2=80=93 so we have three variables:<br><br>
    <strong>(1)</strong> The dichotomous responses for the first of your re=
lated groups (e.g., <span class=3D"n-variable">surprise_exam</span>, which =
reflects whether students "Passed" or "Failed" their <strong>surprise exam<=
/strong>);<br><br>
    <strong>(2)</strong> The dichotomous responses for the second of your r=
elated groups (e.g., <span class=3D"n-variable">mock_exam</span>, which ref=
lects whether students "Passed" or "Failed" their <strong>mock exam</strong=
>); and<br><br>
     <strong>(3)</strong> The dichotomous responses for the third of your r=
elated groups (e.g., <span class=3D"n-variable">final_exam</span>, which re=
flects whether students "Passed" or "Failed" their <strong>final exam</stro=
ng>).<br><br>
  In addition, if you have entered your data into SPSS Statistics using fre=
quencies (i.e., total counts) rather than entering the individual scores fo=
r each participant, you will have one more variable, <strong>frequencies</s=
trong> (i.e., captured in the variable, <span class=3D"s-variable">freq</sp=
an>).</p>
=09
    <p>In the diagram below, we show you how you would have set up your dat=
a in the <strong>Data View</strong> of SPSS Statistics if you had entered y=
our data using: (a) the individual scores for each participant (shown in th=
e diagram on the left below), where you only have three variables; or (b) t=
otal count data, also known as frequencies (shown in the diagram on the rig=
ht below), where you have four variables.</p>

	<div class=3D"spss-image spss-image-text" style=3D"max-width:885px;max-hei=
ght:661px;">
<img src=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/img/cqt/data-setup-=
cochrans-q-test.png" data-src=3D"img/cqt/data-setup-cochrans-q-test.png" al=
t=3D"Shows 'Data View' in SPSS Statistics for Cochran's Q test using indivi=
dual scores for each participant and frequencies" width=3D"100%">
<p>Published with written permission from SPSS Statistics, IBM Corporation.=
</p>
</div>
=09
   <p>Just remember that if you have entered your data using total count da=
ta (i.e., frequencies), shown in the diagram on the right above, you will a=
lso have to <strong>weight your cases</strong> before you can analyse your =
data (i.e., this is an additional procedure in SPSS Statistics). If you do =
not use the <strong>Weight cases...</strong> procedure in SPSS Statistics b=
efore running  Cochran's <em>Q</em> test procedure in the next section, you=
r analysis will fail.</p>

	<p class=3D"note" style=3D"margin-left: 10px;margin-right: 10px;"><span cl=
ass=3D"note-title">Note:</span> If you are unsure how to set up your data i=
n SPSS Statistics for the two data setup scenarios above, we explain how to=
 do this in our enhanced Cochran's <em>Q</em> test guide. We also provide t=
wo data files =E2=80=93 one for each of the two data  setups above =E2=80=
=93 so that you can practice using our example before running Cochran's <em=
>Q</em> test on your own data.</p>
 =09
  	<a name=3D"procedure"></a>
	<h6>SPSS Statistics</h6>
	<h2><strong>SPSS Statistics procedure</strong> to carry out Cochran's <em>=
Q</em> test</h2>
=09
	<p>The four steps below show you how to analyse your data using the "stand=
ard" Cochran's <em>Q</em> test in SPSS Statistics. At the end of these four=
 steps, we show you how to interpret the results from this test.</p>=20
	=09
	<p class=3D"note" style=3D"margin-left: 10px;margin-right: 10px;"><span cl=
ass=3D"note-title">Note 1:</span> We show you the <strong>Legacy Dialogs &g=
t; K Related Samples</strong> procedure in SPSS Statistics to run Cochran's=
 <em>Q</em> test below because this can be used with a wide range of versio=
ns of SPSS Statistics. However, you can also run Cochran's <em>Q</em> test =
using the <strong>Nonparametric Tests &gt; Related Samples</strong> procedu=
re in SPSS Statistics, which is available for <strong>versions 18 to 30</st=
rong> and the <strong>subscription version</strong> of SPSS Statistics. Thi=
s <strong>Nonparametric Tests &gt; Related Samples</strong> procedure provi=
des <strong>additional statistics</strong> and <strong>more graphical optio=
ns</strong> than the <strong>Legacy Dialogs &gt; K Related Samples</strong>=
 procedure. Therefore, we show you how to run the <strong>Nonparametric Tes=
ts &gt; Related Samples</strong> procedure and interpret and report the out=
put from it in our enhanced Cochran's <em>Q</em> test guide. You can access=
 the enhanced Cochran's <em>Q</em> test guide by <a href=3D"https://statist=
ics.laerd.com/pricing.php">subscribing to Laerd Statistics</a>. </p>
=09
	<p class=3D"note" style=3D"margin-left: 10px;margin-right: 10px;"><span cl=
ass=3D"note-title">Note 2:</span> The procedure that follows is <strong>ide=
ntical</strong> for SPSS Statistics <strong>versions 17 to 30</strong>, as =
well as the <strong>subscription version</strong> of SPSS Statistics, with =
<strong>version 30</strong> and the <strong>subscription version</strong> b=
eing the <strong>latest versions</strong> of SPSS Statistics. However, in <=
strong>version 27</strong> and the <strong>subscription version</strong>, S=
PSS Statistics introduced a new look to their interface called "<strong>SPS=
S Light</strong>", replacing the previous look for <strong>versions 26</str=
ong> and <strong>earlier versions</strong>, which was called "<strong>SPSS =
Standard</strong>". Therefore, if you have SPSS Statistics <strong>versions=
 27 to 30</strong> (or the <strong>subscription version</strong> of SPSS St=
atistics), the images that follow will be light grey rather than blue. Howe=
ver, the procedure is <strong>identical</strong>.</p>
=09
	<ol>
	=09
<li>Click <strong><u>A</u>nalyze &gt; <u>N</u>onparametric Tests &gt; <u>L<=
/u>egacy Dialogs &gt; K Related <u>S</u>amples...</strong> on the main menu=
, as shown below:
<div class=3D"spss-image" style=3D"max-width:905px;max-height:680px;">
<img src=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/img/cqt/menu-cochra=
ns-q-test.png" data-src=3D"img/cqt/menu-cochrans-q-test.png" alt=3D"Menu fo=
r Cochran's Q test in SPSS Statistics" width=3D"100%">
<p>Published with written permission from SPSS Statistics, IBM Corporation.=
</p>
</div>=20
<br>You will be presented with the <strong>Tests for Several Related Sample=
s</strong> dialogue box, as shown below:<br>
<div class=3D"spss-image" style=3D"max-width:471px;max-height:357px;">
<img src=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/img/cqt/options-coc=
hrans-q-test.png" data-src=3D"img/cqt/options-cochrans-q-test.png" alt=3D"'=
Test of Several Related Samples' dialogue box with 3 variables, 'surprise_e=
xam', 'mock_exam', and 'final_exam', on the left" width=3D"100%">
<p>Published with written permission from SPSS Statistics, IBM Corporation.=
</p>
</div>
</li>
	=09
<li>Transfer the variables <span class=3D"n-variable">surprise_exam</span>,=
 <span class=3D"n-variable">mock_exam</span> and <span class=3D"n-variable"=
>final_exam</span> into the <span class=3D"boxes"><u>T</u>est Variables:</s=
pan> box by dragging-and-dropping or by clicking the <img src=3D"https://st=
atistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/img/cqt/button-right-arrow.png" data-src=
=3D"img/cqt/button-right-arrow.png" alt=3D"Right arrow" width=3D"32" height=
=3D"30" class=3D"spss-image-in-text" title=3D"SPSS Statistics right arrow b=
utton"> button. You will end up with a screen similar to the one below:
<div class=3D"spss-image" style=3D"max-width:471px;max-height:357px;">
<img src=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/img/cqt/options-exa=
mple-cochrans-q-test.png" data-src=3D"img/cqt/options-example-cochrans-q-te=
st.png" alt=3D"'Test of Several Related Samples' dialogue box. The 3 variab=
les have been transferred into 'Test Variables' box on the right" width=3D"=
100%">
<p>Published with written permission from SPSS Statistics, IBM Corporation.=
</p>
</div>=20
</li>
	=09
<li>Make sure that you uncheck the <span class=3D"cns-variable"><u>F</u>rie=
dman</span> checkbox (it is selected by default in SPSS Statistics) and che=
ck the <span class=3D"cs-variable"><u>C</u>ochran's Q</span> checkbox in th=
e <span class=3D"areas">=E2=80=93Test Type=E2=80=93</span> area, as shown b=
elow:=20
<div class=3D"spss-image" style=3D"max-width:471px;max-height:357px;">
<img src=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/img/cqt/options-exa=
mple-2-cochrans-q-test.png" data-src=3D"img/cqt/options-example-2-cochrans-=
q-test.png" alt=3D"'Test of Several Related Samples' dialogue box where 'Co=
chran's Q' option has been selected" width=3D"100%">
<p>Published with written permission from SPSS Statistics, IBM Corporation.=
</p>
</div>
</li>
	=09
<li>Click on the <img src=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/im=
g/cqt/button-ok.png" data-src=3D"img/cqt/button-ok.png" class=3D"spss-image=
-in-text" alt=3D"OK" height=3D"24" width=3D"51"> button to generate the out=
put.
</li>
	=09
</ol>

<p>Now that you have run the "standard" Cochran's <em>Q</em> test procedure=
, we show you how to interpret and report your results.</p>
		=09
	</div><div class=3D"prices" style=3D"height:84px;background:#369;margin-bo=
ttom:20px;margin-top:20px;"><div class=3D"primary" style=3D"width:980px;mar=
gin:0 auto;"><span style=3D"display:block;width:550px;text-align:center;fon=
t-family:Georgia;font-size:20px;color:#fff;font-style:italic;padding-top:15=
px;padding-left:0px;float:left;">Join the 10,000s of students, academics an=
d professionals who rely on Laerd Statistics.</span><span style=3D"display:=
block;float:right;margin-top:22px;"><a class=3D"apply-button" style=3D"padd=
ing:14px 48px;margin-right:10px;" href=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/feat=
ures-overview.php">TAKE THE TOUR</a><a class=3D"sign-up-button" href=3D"htt=
ps://statistics.laerd.com/pricing.php">PLANS &amp; PRICING</a></span></div>=
</div><div class=3D"container">
=09
	<h6>SPSS Statistics</h6>
	<h2><strong>Interpreting</strong> the SPSS Statistics output for Cochran's=
 <em>Q</em> test</h2>
=09
	<p>SPSS Statistics generates two main tables of output for the "standard" =
Cochran's <em>Q</em> test when using the <strong>Legacy Dialogs &gt; K Rela=
ted Samples</strong> procedure: the <strong>Frequencies</strong> table and =
<strong>Test Statistics</strong> table. These are discussed in turn below:<=
/p>
=09
	<p class=3D"note" style=3D"margin-left: 10px;margin-right: 10px;"><span cl=
ass=3D"note-title">Note:</span> We refer to the "standard" Cochran's <em>Q<=
/em> test because if you violated the sample size assumption discussed <a h=
ref=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/cochrans-q-test-in-spss-=
statistics.php#assumption4">above</a>, such that you had to run an "exact" =
version of Cochran's <em>Q</em> test, the results below may not be accurate=
. However, from this point forward, we will just refer to Cochran's <em>Q</=
em> test rather than the "standard" Cochran's <em>Q</em> test for ease.</p>
=09
	<h3>Frequencies Table</h3>
=09
	<p>It is important when reporting Cochran's <em>Q</em> test result that yo=
u also interpret and report descriptive statistics in order to get a 'feel'=
 for your data, as well as to provide an appropriate description of your da=
ta. One important measure that we can report is the number of participants =
that passed and failed each of the three exams: the surprise exam, mock exa=
m and final exam. This is illustrated in the results generated in the <stro=
ng>Frequencies</strong> table, as shown below:</p>
=09
	<div class=3D"spss-image spss-image-text" style=3D"max-width:270px;max-hei=
ght:182px;">
    <img src=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/img/cqt/output-=
cochrans-q-test.png" data-src=3D"img/cqt/output-cochrans-q-test.png" alt=3D=
"'Frequencies' table for Cochran's Q test. 3 variables shown along the 3 ro=
ws. '1' and '2' columns displayed under 'Value'" width=3D"100%">
	<p>Published with written permission from SPSS Statistics, IBM Corporation=
.</p>
	</div>
   =20
	 <p class=3D"note" style=3D"margin-left: 10px;margin-right: 10px;"><span c=
lass=3D"note-title">Note:</span> The titles in the <strong>Value</strong> c=
olumn will reflect the coding you used when setting up your three or more v=
ariables in the <strong>Variable View</strong> of SPSS Statistics. In our e=
xample, "<strong>1</strong>" reflects the number of students who "<strong>f=
ailed</strong>" the exam and "<strong>2</strong>" reflects the number of st=
udents who "<strong>passed</strong>" the exam. The left-hand column will co=
nsist of the three or more variables in your study (i.e., "Surprise exam", =
"Mock exam" and "Final exam" in our example).</p>
=09
	<p>You can see from the <strong>Frequencies</strong> table that 53 student=
s failed and 7 students passed the surprise exam, whereas 36 students faile=
d and 24 passed the mock exam. Finally, 20 students failed the final exam, =
whereas 40 passed. In the sense that the study was designed to evaluate the=
 change in the proportion of pass and failure rates as student had more tim=
e to revise, it appears that failure rates decreased across the three exams=
 (i.e., as students had more time to revise). However, although it can appe=
ar that these proportions are different, the differences could simply be du=
e to sampling variation. Therefore, to establish whether these proportions =
of passes are different in the population and are not simply due to samplin=
g variation, you need to consult the Cochran's <em>Q</em> test result, as s=
et out in the next section.</p>

	<h3>Test Statistics Table</h3>
=09
    <p>Now that we know the proportion of students who passed and failed th=
e three exams =E2=80=93 the surprise, mock and final exams =E2=80=93 we wou=
ld like to know whether these proportions are statistically significantly d=
ifferent. To know this, we can use the result of Cochran's <em>Q</em> test,=
 which can be found in the <strong>Test Statistics</strong> table below:</p=
>
=09
	    <div class=3D"spss-image spss-image-text" style=3D"max-width:191px;max=
-height:193px;">
    <img src=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/img/cqt/output-=
2-cochrans-q-test.png" data-src=3D"img/cqt/output-2-cochrans-q-test.png" al=
t=3D"'Test Statistics' table for Cochran's Q test where rows show 'N', 'Coc=
hran's Q', 'df' &amp; 'Asymp. Sig.'. '1' treated as success" width=3D"100%"=
>
	<p>Published with written permission from SPSS Statistics, IBM Corporation=
.</p>
  </div>
=09
	<p>If the statistical significance value (i.e., <em>p</em>-value) is less =
than .05 (i.e., <em>p</em> &lt; .05), you have a statistically significant =
result and the proportion of students who passed and failed their exams acr=
oss the three exams is statistically significantly different. Alternatively=
, if <em>p</em> &gt; .05, you do not have a statistically significant resul=
t and the proportion of students who passed and failed their exams across t=
he three exams is not statistically significantly different (i.e., the prop=
ortion of passes does not change over the course of the exams as students h=
ave more time to revise). In our example, <em>p</em> =3D .000 (i.e., <em>p<=
/em> &lt; .0005), which means that the proportion of students who passed th=
eir exams is statistically significantly different across the three exams.<=
/p>
  =20
   <div class=3D"decision" style=3D"background:#005292;color:#fff;padding:3=
0px 60px;">
		<div class=3D"signpost"></div>
	  <div class=3D"dp">
			<h2 style=3D"color:#fff;border-bottom: 1px dotted #fff;font-family:myria=
d-pro;margin-bottom:0;margin-top:0;padding:0;">Decision Time</h2>
			<p><strong>Option 1: </strong>If you <strong>do not</strong> have a stat=
istically significant Cochran's <em>Q</em> test =E2=80=93 using either the =
"standard" Cochran's <em>Q</em> test or the "exact" version of Cochran's <e=
m>Q</em> test =E2=80=93 you <strong>do not</strong> need to run a post hoc =
test. You can go straight to our <a href=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/sp=
ss-tutorials/cochrans-q-test-in-spss-statistics.php#reporting">Reporting</a=
> section.</p>
		<p><strong>Option 2:</strong> If you have a statistically significant Coc=
hran's <em>Q</em> test using the "standard" Cochran's <em>Q</em> test, you =
can carry out a post hoc test using either Dunn's test (which also automati=
cally applies a Bonferroni correction) or multiple McNemar's tests (where y=
ou need to make a manual Bonferroni correction).</p>
		<p><strong>Option 3:</strong> If you have a statistically significant Coc=
hran's <em>Q</em> test using the "exact" version of Cochran's <em>Q</em> te=
st, you can carry out a post hoc test using multiple McNemar's tests (where=
 you need to make a manual  Bonferroni correction).</p>
		  <p>If you have a statistically significant result and want to carry on =
with your analysis using a post hoc test (i.e., either <strong>Option 2</st=
rong> or <strong>Option 3</strong> above), we show you how to do this in ou=
r enhanced guide, which is available if you choose to <a href=3D"https://st=
atistics.laerd.com/pricing.php">become a member of Laerd Statistics</a>. Th=
is includes an explanation of: (a) the SPSS Statistics procedures required =
to carry out Dunn's post hoc test or multiple McNemar's tests (with Bonferr=
oni correction); (b) how to interpret the results from both of these post h=
oc tests, including how to interpret these results when you met or violated=
 the sample size assumption of Cochran's <em>Q</em> test, which was briefly=
 set out <a href=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/cochrans-q-=
test-in-spss-statistics.php#assumption4">above</a>.
		</p></div>
		<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>
  </div>
<!-- End of Decision Box -->
  =20
    <a name=3D"reporting"></a>
    <h6>SPSS Statistics</h6>
	<h2><strong>Reporting</strong> the results from Cochran's <em>Q</em> test<=
/h2>
=09
	<p>Based on the SPSS Statistics output above, we could report the results =
of the study as follows:</p>
=09
	<div class=3D"statement">
		<ul><li class=3D"gen active">General</li></ul>
		<p class=3D"gen-content">Sixty participants were recruited to take part i=
n study to examine whether pass rates changed over three exams =E2=80=93 a =
surprise, mock and final exam =E2=80=93 as students had more time to study.=
 Cochran's <em>Q</em> test determined that there was a statistically signif=
icant difference in the proportion of students who passed their exams over =
time, =CF=87<sup>2</sup>(2) =3D 49.515, <em>p</em> &lt; .0005.</p>
	<div style=3D"clear:both;"></div>
	</div>
